Ekiti State government has approved six months (180 days) maternity leave for female workers in the state public service. Governor Kayode Fayemi who gave approval said it is in line with the administration’s determination to key into global best practices that will improve the quality of lives of the citizens. The new policy, which takes effect from February 1, 2020 according to him, is aimed at improving maternal health. The governor in a statement signed by his chief press secretary, Mr Yinka Oyebode, explained that the policy was also to encourage nursing mothers to observe the six months exclusive breast feeding campaign of the United Nations Intervention Children’s Emergency Fund (UNICEF). The six months exclusive breast feeding campaign will assist in reducing to the barest minimum, infant and maternal mortality rate as well as facilitate work life balance for female workers in the state The Ekiti State government has continues to show strong political will towards ensuring gender inclusiveness This policy is one of many other frameworks in place aimed at promoting the rights of women and children. 